Cyclone Idai has triggered a “massive disaster” in southern Africa affecting hundreds of thousands if not millions of people, the UN says. The region has been hit by flooding and devastation affecting Mozambique, Zimbabwe and Malawi. Mozambique President Filipe Nyusi has called it “a humanitarian disaster of great proportion”. He said more than 1,000 people may have been killed after the cyclone hit the country last week. Cyclone Idai made landfall near the port city of Beira in Sofala province on Thursday with winds of up to 177 km/h. “We need all the logistical support that we can get, “ Christian Lindmeier from the UN’s World Health Organization said. MOZAMBIQUE: Mozambique braces for tropical cyclone MOZAMBIQUE Cyclone Idai: President says 1,000 may have died Cyclone: Buhari condoles with Mozambique, Zimbabwe, Malawi